text: Engineering Atypical Tetracycline Formation in Amycolatopsis sulphurea for the Production of Modiﬁed Chelocardin Antibiotics Tadeja Lukežič,†,‡,§ Antoine Abou Fayad,†,‡ Chantal Bader,†,‡ Kirsten Harmrolfs,†,‡ Johannes Bartuli,†,‡ Sebastian Groß,†,‡ Urška Lešnik,§,∥ Fabienne Hennessen,†,‡ Jennifer Herrmann,†,‡ Špela Pikl,∥ Hrvoje Petković,*,∥ † Department of Microbial Natural Products, Helmholtz Institute for Pharmaceutical Research Saarland (HIPS), Helmholtz Centre for Infection Research (HZI), and Department of Pharmacy, Saarland University, Campus E8.1, 66123 Saarbrücken, Germany ‡ German Centre for Infection Research (DZIF), Partner site Hannover-Braunschweig, 38124 Braunschweig, Germany § Acies Bio, d.o.o., Tehnološki Park 21, 1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia ∥ Department of Food Science and Technology, Biotechnical Faculty, University of Ljubljana, Jamnikarjeva 101, 1000 Ljubljana, Slovenia *S Supporting Information In these times when there is urgent need for new antibiotics,1 one of the strategies for their development is reanalysis and structural optimization of known chemical scaﬀolds, such as the tetracyclines (Figure 1). Tetracyclines show a broad spectrum of activity against bacterial pathogens and are used to infectious diseases.2−4 Tetracyclines act treat numerous through inhibition of translation, by binding to ribosomes during polypeptide elongation. ABSTRACT: To combat the increasing spread of antimicro- bial resistance and the shortage of novel anti-infectives, one strategy for the development of new antibiotics is to optimize known chemical scaﬀolds. Here, we focus on the biosynthetic engineering of Amycolatopsis sulphurea for derivatization of the atypical tetracycline chelocardin and its potent broad- spectrum derivative 2-carboxamido-2-deacetyl-chelocardin. Heterologous biosynthetic genes were introduced into this chelocardin producer to modify functional groups and generate new derivatives. We demonstrate cooperation of chelocardin polyketide synthase with tailoring enzymes involved in biosynthesis of oxytetracycline from Streptomyces rimosus. An interesting feature of chelocardin, compared with oxytetracycline, is the opposite stereochemistry of the C4 amino group. Genes involved in C4 transamination and N,N-dimethylation of oxytetracycline were heterologously expressed in an A. sulphurea mutant lacking C4-aminotransferase. Chelocardin derivatives with opposite stereochemistry of the C4 amino group, as N,N-dimethyl-epi-chelocardin and N,N-dimethyl-2-carboxamido-2-deacetyl-epi-chelocardin, were produced only when the aminotransferase from oxytetracycline was coexpressed with the N-methyltransferase OxyT. Surprisingly, OxyT exclusively accepted intermediates carrying an S-conﬁgured amino group at C4 in chelocardin. Applying medicinal chemistry approaches, several 2-carboxamido-2-deacetyl-epi-chelocardin derivatives modiﬁed at C4 were produced. Analysis of the antimicrobial activities of the modiﬁed compounds demonstrated that the primary amine in the R conﬁguration is a crucial structural feature for activity of chelocardin. Unexpectedly, C10 glycosylated chelocardin analogues were identiﬁed, thus revealing the glycosylation potential of A. sulphurea. However, eﬃcient glycosylation of the chelocardin backbone occurred only after engineering of a dimethylated

Unexpectedly, C10 glycosylated chelocardin analogues were identiﬁed, thus revealing the glycosylation potential of A. sulphurea. However, eﬃcient glycosylation of the chelocardin backbone occurred only after engineering of a dimethylated amino group at the C4 position in the opposite S conﬁguration, which suggests some evolutionary remains of chelocardin glycosylation.

Chelocardin (CHD; Figure 1)16 is an atypical tetracycline that has broad-spectrum antibiotic activity, and is produced by the actinomycete Amycolatopsis sulphurea. In a report in 1977, CHD showed promise in a small phase II clinical study for patients with urinary tract infections caused by Gram-negative pathogens.17 Importantly, CHD is also active against tetracycline-resistant pathogens, including Gram-negative bacteria.18 The well-known tetracycline scaﬀold is one of the structural characteristics of CHD. However, the CHD structure diﬀers in a number of important ways compared with the so-called typical tetracyclines, including a diﬀerent aromatization pattern, acetyl instead of carboxamido group at DOI: 10.1021/acschembio.8b01125 ACS Chem. Biol. XXXX, XXX, XXX−XXX Figure 3. Proposed biosynthesis of N,N-dimethyl-epi-CDCHD and its glycosylated analogues. SAM, S-adenosyl-L-methionine. carbon 2 [C2], a primary instead of tertiary amine at C4, and an additional methyl group at C9. This is also reﬂected in its diﬀerent mode of action.19,20 However, the molecular target of CHD has not been identiﬁed yet. Applying a biosynthetic engineering approach, a new CHD analogue, 2-carboxamido-2-deacetyl-CHD (CDCHD; Figure 1) was produced by recombinant A. sulphurea.9 CDCHD showed signiﬁcantly improved antimicrobial activity against a collection of well-characterized multidrug-resistant clinical isolates from the ESKAPE panel21 of the most important clinical pathogens. Therefore, CDCHD was selected for further development through medicinal chemistry approaches in an ongoing project. In parallel, a number of CHD and CDCHD analogues were generated using biosynthetic engineering approaches, as

presented here. Interestingly, with CHD, the C4 position of ring A (Figure 1) is occupied by a primary amine in the R- conﬁguration, which is in contrast to the typical tetracyclines that have an S-conﬁgured dimethylamino group in the C4 position, such as oxytetracycline (OTC)22 and chlortetracy- cline (CTC).23 In addition to the intriguing aspects of the underlying biosynthetic mechanisms involved in deﬁning the stereochemistry, this relatively small, but potentially important, structural diﬀerence might have an important role in the activity of CHD. The CHD PKS enzyme complex catalyzes the biosynthesis of the CHD backbone,24 and its successful cooperation with selected post-PKS enyzmes involved in the biosynthesis of OTC22 allowed the generation of novel CHD analogues from the CHD scaﬀold. Surprisingly, while the anticipated N,N- DOI: 10.1021/acschembio.8b01125 ACS Chem. Biol. XXXX, XXX, XXX−XXX Table 1. dimethyl-epi-CHD (Figure 2) and N,N-dimethyl-epi-CDCHD (Figure 3) were generated, some unexpected glycosylated CHD analogues were also produced (see Supporting Information: Figures S15, S20, S26, S31). This revealed the previously hidden glycosylation potential of A. sulphurea, which thus provided further chemical space expansion of CHD. Subsequently, selected CHD analogues derived from bio- synthetic engineering approaches were derivatized further by semisynthesis, to generate novel CDCHD analogues based on the C4 position of the tetracycline scaﬀold. This combination of biosynthetic and semisynthetic approaches not only resulted in new CHD derivatives but also allowed deeper insights into the structure−activity relationships to be gained (Table 1). These can now be readily applied in the further development of novel tetracyclines. On the basis of the development of the potent tetracycline analogue CDCHD that shows improved antimicrobial activity compared to the parent compound, CHD,9 this strategy was employed with the aim of developing novel CHD analogues through the combination of selected genes from the CHD and OTC biosynthetic gene clusters. Of note, this combinatorial biosynthesis strategy is based on the high yield achieved for CDCHD, which makes the production of derivatives feasible at a scale required for downstream applications. N,N-Dimethylation toward New epi-CHD Analogues. One of the key features that distinguishes CHD from other typical tetracyclines is the absence of two methyl groups on the C4 amino group (Figure 1). OxyT is a putative N,N- dimethyltransferase from S. rimosus22 that is believed to dimethylate the C4 amino group in the biosynthesis of OTC. The aim here was to expand the structural diversity of the CHD-based compounds through generation of methylated CHD analogues using heterologous expression of the oxyT gene in A. sulphurea. Surprisingly, introduction into the A. sulphurea wild-type strain of the pAB03 integrative vector containing oxyT from the OTC gene cluster did not result in production of any detectable methylated CHD analogues (expected mass: single methylated CHD analogue, m/z 426; double methylated CHD analogue, m/z 440). This might be explained by the narrow substrate speciﬁcity of the OxyT N,N- dimethyltransferase, as CHD diﬀers from OTC in terms of its backbone aromatization pattern, diﬀerent starter unit (i.e., C2 moiety), methylation at C9, and lack of hydroxyl groups at positions C5 and C6 on the CHD scaﬀold. On the other hand, the C4 amino group is oriented in the opposite (4R) conﬁguration in CHD compared with OTC. activity against Gram-positive indicator strain activity against Gram-negative indicator strain

Therefore, we next attempted to replace the 4R amino group with the respective 4S conﬁguration through biosynthetic engineering. First, the C4-aminotransferase gene chdN in the CHD cluster of A. sulphurea was inactivated by allelic replacement of the chdN gene with the erythromycin-resistance gene. The A. sulphurea strain with deleted chdN (ΔchdN strain) did not produce detectable amounts of the expected 4- keto-CHD biosynthetic intermediate. This intermediate thus most likely degrades under in vivo conditions, considering that a similar instability has been shown for a parallel intermediate in OTC biosynthesis, 4-keto-anhydrotetracycline.25 The 4S- amino group was then introduced into the CHD backbone by heterologous expression of the gene that encodes the C4- aminotransferase oxyQ in the OTC cluster in the A. sulphurea ΔchdN strain. Surprisingly, however, the C4-aminotransferase ChdN from CHD biosynthesis24 and the OxyQ homologue from the OTC cluster only show around 20% amino-acid similarity (alignment by Geneious R11,26 http://www. geneious.com). Indeed, the “in-trans” chromosomal integration of the oxyQ gene using the ΦBT1-based integration vector pAB03oxyQ in A. sulphurea ΔchdN resulted in the production of epi-CHD (m/z 412; see Supporting Information for NMR analysis: Figure S4, Table S3). However, and again surprisingly, a CHD with the correct stereochemistry (i.e., same m/z; shorter retention time) was also identiﬁed using liquid chromatography−mass spectrometry (Figure 4). While we assume that OxyQ added the C4 amino group into the OTC scaﬀold in the S-conﬁguration (i.e., epi-CHD), the C4 amino group of CHD was in the R-conﬁguration. We propose that OxyQ most likely initially catalyzes the transamination reaction on the C4 position of

We propose that OxyQ most likely initially catalyzes the transamination reaction on the C4 position of the putative 4-keto-CHD intermediate to form the S-conﬁguration. This then sponta- neously epimerizes into the R-conﬁguration (Figure 4d), until an equilibrium is reached between the S-conﬁguration and R- conﬁguration, analogous to that for the typical tetracyclines.27 In the separate experiments with A. sulphurea ΔchdN strain containing pAB03oxyQ (see Supporting Information, Figure S1), we have observed epi-CHD as a major product, supporting the idea of OxyQ catalyzing the transamination reaction on the C4 position to form the S-conﬁguration. As expected, expression of the oxyT N,N-dimethyltransferase gene alone (i.e., without the oxyQ gene) in the A. sulphurea ΔchdN mutant did not lead to the production of any new CHD analogue (Figure 4e).

In the next step, the C4-aminotransferase OxyQ and the N,N-dimethyltransferase OxyT from the OTC gene cluster were introduced simultaneously. This was accomplished by chromosomal integration of the pAB03oxyQT vector contain- ing the oxyQT genes into in the A. sulphurea ΔchdN mutant strain. Liquid chromatography−mass spectrometry analysis of the culture extract of this pAB03oxyQT-containing A. sulphurea ΔchdN strain identiﬁed relatively high production of a compound with mass m/z 440 (Figure 4f; up to 200 mg L−1). The structure of the isolated compound was later conﬁrmed by NMR as N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD (see Supporting Information, Figures S5−S9, Table S4). Interestingly, methyl- ation of the C4 amino group by the OxyT N,N-dimethyl- transferase from the OTC gene cluster was very eﬃcient, considering that no compound of m/z 412, as either CHD or epi-CHD, was detected in the extract of the pAB03oxyQT- containing A. it can be concluded that the opposite stereochemistry of the amino group in the C4 position on the CHD scaﬀold is the main sulphurea ΔchdN mutant. Thus, in addition to C4 transamination and N,N-dimethylation, there was also simultaneous replacement of the C2 position of CHD by a carboxamido group, through the OxyD amidotransferase and the putative acyltransferase OxyP. This latter activity has already been demonstrated for CDCHD biosynthesis, by Lešnik et al.9 Interestingly, expression of the oxyDPQ genes (i.e., the previous combination without the gene for OxyT methyltranferase) in the A. sulphurea ΔchdN mutant only led to minor amounts of the expected new analogue epi-CDCHD (m/z 413) (Figure 5f). However, when the methyltransferase gene oxyT was added to the oxyDPQ set of genes (i.e., oxyDPQT), the methylated CDCHD analogue (Figure 5g) reached production yields that were comparable to those of the methylated CHD analogue described above (Figure 4f).

Glycosylated Analogues of epi-CHDs. In the analysis of the methylated CHD analogues in the engineered A. sulphurea ΔchdN mutant strains containing oxyQT and oxyDPQT, relatively high yields (up to 150 mg L−1) were observed for epi-CHD-related metabolites with masses m/z 586 and m/z 572 and with masses m/z 587 and m/z 573 (Figure 6) in cultures that produced N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD and N,N- dimethyl-epi-CDCHD, further analysis using mass spectroscopy, and by comparison of this data set with the mass of CHD and CDCHD, these compounds appeared to be the glycosylated CHD analogues. Thus, compound 586-2 and compound 587-2 appeared to be glycosylated N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD and N,N-dimethyl-epi- CDCHD, respectively, showing the additional the glycosyl unit with mass of 146 Da, while compounds 572-2 and 573-2 appeared to be their respective derivatives that lacked one methyl group. Indeed, isolation of the target metabolites and structure elucidation by NMR conﬁrmed this hypothesis: compound 586-2 was 10-rhamnosyl-N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD (see Supporting Information, Figure S15), compound 572-2 was 10-rhamnosyl-N,N-dimethyl-9-desmethyl-epi-CHD (see Supporting Information, Figure S20), compound 587-2 was 10-rhamnosyl-N,N-dimethyl-epi-CDCHD (see Supporting In- formation, Figure S26), and compound 573-2 was 10- rhamnosyl-N,N-dimethyl-9-desmethyl-epi-CDCHD (see Sup- porting Information, Figure S31). Furthermore, C4 epimers of compound 586-2 and compound 572-2 were isolated from the sulphurea ΔchdN strain containing broth extract of A. pAB03oxyQT, and designated as compound 586-1 and compound 572-1, respectively, while C

epimers of compound 586-2 and compound 572-2 were isolated from the sulphurea ΔchdN strain containing broth extract of A. pAB03oxyQT, and designated as compound 586-1 and compound 572-1, respectively, while C4 epimers of compound 587-2 and compound 573-2 were isolated from the broth extract of A. sulphurea ΔchdN strain containing pAB03ox- yDPQT, and designated as compound 587-1 and compound 573-1, respectively. Surprisingly, comparisons of the yields of these glycosylated analogues with those of CHD and CDCHD showed that in the engineered A. sulphurea ΔchdN strain that contained oxyQT and oxyDPQT, these glycosylated derivatives of N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD and N,N-dimethyl-epi-CDCHD, respectively, were produced as one of the major CHD-related compounds. These reached yields that were almost comparable to CHD production in wild-type A. sulphurea (see Supporting Information, Figure S2). the glycosylated analogues of CHD and CDCHD were only present as minor compounds, as discussed below.

Interestingly, in addition to the expected com- pounds with m/z 412 and m/z 413 (corresponding to CHD and CDCHD, respectively), compounds with m/z 558 and m/ z 559, respectively (data not shown), were also identiﬁed. These corresponded to CHD and CDCHD derivatives, respectively, which appeared to contain a sugar moiety, thus these adding 146 Da to the molecular weight. Furthermore, in these CHD- and CDCHD-producing strains, there were even lower concentrations of putative glycosylated 9-desmethyl-CHD and 9-desmethyl-CDCHD, with m/z 544 and m/z 545, respectively (data not shown). Interestingly, there were traces of a compound with m/z 544, which corresponds to the putatively glycosylated 9-desmethyl-CHD (i.e., addition of 146 Da sugar) in the engineered strains that produced 9-desmethyl-CHD as a major product (as described the putative glycosylated below). Thus, compounds in cultures that produced CHD and CDCHD have a C4 amino group in the R-conﬁguration (Figure 2, Figure 3), as for CHD and CDCHD themselves, while the C4 amino group would have the opposite conﬁguration for the putative glycosylated compounds in the A. sulphurea ΔchdN mutant with the oxyQ C4-aminotransferase gene introduced. The respective compounds showed shifts in their retention times toward later elution, which was also observed between CHD and epi-CHD in the wild-type strain (Figure 4a), and for the epimers of glycosylated CHDs (Figure 6). Due to the much lower yields of these putative glycosylated derivatives of CHD and CDCHD, we can only speculate that N,N-dimethyl- epi-CHD and N,N-dimethyl-epi-CDCHD represent the cata- lytically more appropriate substrates for glycosylation.

The identiﬁcation of glycosylated CHD analogues was not all that surprising, considering that the CHD gene cluster contains a gene putatively involved in glycosylation (chdGIV),24 which was previously believed to be redundant. ChdGIV showed high similarity (38−41% identity) to O- glycosyltransferases encoded in biosynthetic gene clusters for polyketomycin,28 dutomycin,29 chromomycin,30 and mithra- mycin.31,32 ChdGIV also shares homology with the land- omycin A glycosyltransferase LanGT233 (31% identity) and the jadomycin B glycosyltransferase JadS34 (27% identity), both of which glycosylate the hydroxy group at position C10 (CHD numbering orientation). The structures of the glycosylated compounds isolated from culture extracts of N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD- and N,N-dimethyl- epi-CDCHD-producing cultures were conﬁrmed to contain a rhamnosyl unit attached to the C10 position by NMR analysis (Figures S15−S36, Tables S7−S13). However, inactivation of chdGIV from the CHD gene cluster showed, surprisingly, that ChdGIV from this gene cluster was not involved in glycosylation of CHD, nor of N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD, as the glycosylated analogues of CHD were still produced at the same yields (data not shown). On the other hand, there are a few other putative glycosyltransferase genes in A. sulphurea outside the CHD gene cluster that might be responsible for this modiﬁcation, which demonstrates the hidden potential of cross-talk between diverse gene clusters inside the same genome.

C9-Methylation in the Biosynthesis of CHDs. Gene inactivation using allelic replacement of the methyltransferase gene chdMII through a double-crossover event was applied to construct a strain of A. sulphurea ΔchdMII that produced 9- desmethyl-CHD (9DMCHD), with mass m/z 398, and that reached yields of up to 80 mg L−1 (see Supporting Information, Figure S3). For the pNV18chdMIIErm plasmid was constructed and introduced into the wild-type strain of A. sulphurea, which was then subcultivated in the absence of the antibiotic marker to select for double-crossover mutants. While the recombinants no longer produced CHD, a new CHD analogue that lacked the C9 methyl group (9DMCHD) was detected in the culture broth (see Supporting Information, Figure S3). To quickly identify 9DMCHD in the culture broth of these recombinants, MS/MS analysis was used, as described in our previous study.35 Here, 9DMCHD was ﬁnally isolated, and its structure was conﬁrmed by NMR (see Supporting Information, Figures S37−S41, Table S14). A smaller amount of 9DMCHD was also seen for the culture broth of the wild-type strain (around 1% of the CHD yield; see Supporting Information, Figure S3), which was largely as expected, as C9-methylation likely occurs as one of the last steps in CHD biosynthesis,24 which would leave some of the unprocessed biosynthetic intermediate. Interestingly, only traces of N,N- dimethyl-9-desmethyl-epi-CHD and N,N-dimethyl-9-desmeth- yl-epi-CDCHD were produced alongside N,N-dimethyl-epi- CHD and N,N-dimethyl-epi-CDCHD, respectively. Semisynthesis toward C4-Modiﬁed CDCHD Ana- logues. To expand the chemical space of the CHDs further, a semisynthetic approach was applied for derivatization of CDCHD produced through biosynthetic approaches. Diﬀerent moieties were added onto the C4 position through peptide coupling chemistry, where HATU and HOBt were used as the coupling reagents in the presence of N,N-diisopropylethyl- amine as a base (see Supporting Information, “Semisynthesis of CDCHD derivatives and nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy analysis”). Tetrahydrofuran was used as the solvent, and yields of 70% and higher were achieved. Derivatives and their epimers were isolated, and their structures conﬁrmed by NMR (see Supporting Information, “Semisynthesis of CDCHD derivatives and nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy analysis”).

Antimicrobial Activity of Isolated CHD Analogues. All of the CHD analogues isolated in suﬃcient quantities were analyzed for their activities against Staphylococcus aureus, Klebsiella pneumoniae, Pseudomonas aeruginosa, and Escherichia coli indicator strains (see Supporting Information, Table S1). Through biosynthetic and semisynthetic modiﬁcations, diﬀer- ent positions of the CHD backbone were targeted, corresponding to C2, C4, C9, and C10, and 19 new analogues were isolated, as presented in Table 1. Biosynthetic engineering to change the primary amines of CHD and CDCHD on position C4 to tertiary amines and at the same time to invert the conﬁguration from R to S generally resulted in loss of activity. While signiﬁcant decreases in the activities against the Gram-positive indicator strains were observed in most cases, the activities against the Gram-negative indicator strains showed more pronounced decreases, which generally resulted in practically inactive compounds (Table 1, Supporting Information, Tables S20, S21). Another insight into the structure−activity relationships of the CHDs (Table 1) was gained by modiﬁcation of CDCHD through semisyn- thesis, where diﬀerent functional groups were added to the C4 amino group of CDCHD (see Supporting Information, Figures S42−S46). In most cases, both C4 epimers were isolated, and these were tested for antimicrobial activities (see Supporting Information, Table S22). Again, and independent of the stereochemical position of the substituent at C4, the activity against the Gram-negative strains was lost, probably due to the loss of an ionizable functional group. The importance of primary amines for activity against Gram-negative bacteria was recently shown by Richter et al.,36 who investigated the accumulation of over 180 diverse compounds in E. coli. Interestingly, primary amines are not common in natural products, and they are largely absent from many screening collections,36 which is another argument that makes CHD and CDCHD valuable lead compounds.

Furthermore, as known from the literature and as also conﬁrmed in our laboratory, 4-epi-CHD has the C4 amino group in the S-conﬁguration, as found in typical tetracyclines, and it shows lower antimicrobial activity compared with CHD.37 Also, the structures of N,N-dimethyl-epi-CHD and N,N-dimethyl-epi-CDCHD resemble anhydrotetracyclines (i.e., anhydrotetracycline, anhydrochlortetracycline, 4-epi-anhy- drotetracycline, 4-epi-anhydrochlortetracycline; see Supporting Information, Figure S47), which are substantially less active against Gram-negative bacteria when compared to typical tetracyclines.19 In general, addition of a carbohydrate moiety as seen for compounds 586-2, 572-2, 587-2, and 573-2 positively inﬂuences the physicochemical properties of these molecules increased water solubility, better bioavailability).38 To (e.g., further investigate the properties of the glycosylated CHDs, addition of a carbohydrate moiety to the parent molecules (i.e., CHD, CDCHD) appears to provide the greatest beneﬁts, particularly considering that other backbone modiﬁcations to the C4 and C9 positions abolish the activities against Gram- negative bacteria. Surprisingly, removal of the methyl group at C9 resulted in a virtually inactive compound, 9DMCHD, with only minor activity against S. aureus (see Supporting Information, Table S21); thus, this moiety also has an essential role in the bioactivity. This was unexpected, considering that such C9 derivatization of the glycylcyclines does not cause loss of their antibacterial activities.39

The present study highlights two more important diﬀerences between the scaﬀolds of typical tetracyclines and CHD: the carboxamido starter, and the C4-dimethylamino groups. These are both essential for the activities of typical tetracyclines, and they contribute strongly to tetracycline binding to the ribosome. However, as indicated above, the CHD backbone diﬀers from typical tetracyclines also in its aromatization pattern, which most probably reduces the binding aﬃnity of CHD for the primary target of tetracyclines, the ribosome.2,40 The reason for diﬀerent aromatization patterns in tetracycline compared with the CHD backbone lies in the last steps of tetracycline biosynthesis, which are not part of the biosynthesis of CHD. These are C6 hydroxylation of anhydrotetracycline and the following C5a−C11a reduction,41 which change the relatively planar structure of anhydrotetracycline with its two aromatic rings (rings C, D) into the more bent three- dimensional structure of tetracycline with only one aromatic ring (ring D) and a kink between rings A and B. Finally, the importance of the C9-methyl group for activity of CHD is intriguing as its removal resulted in the virtually inactive compound 9DMCHD. This is, however, not the case in tetracycline antibiotics,39 strongly underpinning our hypothesis that the mode of action of CHD and its derivatives is diﬀerent from that of the typical tetracyclines, such as OTC, where the primary target is the ribosome.2,40

It should be emphasized that even though the type II PKS biosynthetic machinery is composed of discrete monofunc- tional enzymes, the entire set of enzymes operates as a complex, where the absence of one partner protein can lead to incorrect activity of the entire PKS machinery, which will result in formation of aberrant products.42,43 Indeed, we succeeded here in complementing the missing aminotransferase ChdN of the CHD complex in the A. sulphurea ΔchdN mutant strain with a relatively distant homologue aminotransferase, OxyQ, from the OTC complex, which resulted in the formation of an epimer of CHD. Furthermore, we achieved simultaneous cooperation of many diﬀerent enzymes from the OTC gene DOI: 10.1021/acschembio.8b01125 ACS Chem. Biol. XXXX, XXX, XXX−XXX cluster with the CHD biosynthetic machinery, which led to the production of a number of CHD analogues.

We have gained important understanding of the enzymology and, the the stereochemical heterologously expressed methyltransferase OxyT from the OTC gene cluster. This turns out to have exclusive substrate speciﬁcity for an intermediate with an S-conﬁgured amino group at the C4 position of the CHD scaﬀold. We have also shown that A. sulphurea has the potential to glycosylate CHD analogues through an as yet unknown glycosyltransferase, which appears to be active and functional only after the CHD scaﬀold is modiﬁed with the N,N-dimethylamino moiety in the S-conﬁguration at C4. We speculate that the A. sulphurea major product, CHD, suitable substrate for glycosylation. The presence of a glycosyltranferase in the CHD gene cluster, and particularly the eﬃcient glycosylation activity of engineered CHD metabolites in the S-conﬁguration at the C4 position by an unknown glycosyltransferase present in A. suphurea, suggests some evolutionary remains that were unexpectedly activated in the scope of the biosynthetic engineering carried out in the present study. The tetracycline and CHD analogues that resulted from the combined approaches of biosynthetic engineering and semi- synthesis have provided further understanding of the structure−activity relationships of CHD, which can be used in future eﬀorts to develop novel and more potent tetracycline antibiotics. To conclude, we have demonstrated that the mixing and matching of genes encoding the CHD and OTC biosynthetic enzymes to form hybrid enzyme complexes can be eﬃcient and lead to the generation of new tetracycline analogues. Finally, considering the vast amount of genomic information currently available in databases that is related to secondary metabolite biosynthesis, we have demonstrated the versatility of the combined biosynthetic and semisynthetic approaches used in the present study that can be applied in future drug development.
